From those that I know, being the Pueblo, Mississippian, and Karankawa, were remarked as having extreme value placed on monogamy, and engaging in intercourse was seen as marriage among the (now extinct) Karankawa from what can be inferred. The Pueblo and Mississippian were on their last legs when the Indo-European groups arrived, but the Spanish and French remarked the Caddo and Wichita (both of whom were Mississippian remnant cultures) familial and matrimonial traditions to Catholic Europe so it can be assumed virginity was important.
Some of the early legends about El Dorado that I've found noted that "all unwed women were maidens, and they would offer you their hand and maidenhood."
El Dorado was a reference to the wealth of the Pueblo people, again, from what we can infer today.

However, a big point of difference is that the women pursued the men in most Native American societies, and men were expected to keep it in their pants for free women as slaves were free game to fuck. That being said, I don't know much about the East Coast Indians, but with how important diplomatic marriages and heirs were within the Iroquois and Cherokee people virginity, especially among females, would be of the utmost importance to ensure a child is their father's son.

As for the plains indians, nomads are generally value virginity extremely high, see the Abrahamic Faiths and Indo-Europeans faiths, both of whom descended from nomads and were monotheistic as were the plains Indians with their Great Spirit. Cultural parallels normally don't work so well between the Old and New world but knowing where the Natives' ancestors came from does permit some shared values with the Siberian natives of whom value virginity.

As for Africa and why I haven't used any parallels from their is that there can be none made, Africa is a different beast, and is culturally alien to the rest of the planet more than the native americans were oddly enough.
